	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">ComR transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Copper , silver , and gold released ComR from the DNA , but also formed some protein aggregates of intermediate mobility , apparent as dark smears ( Fig. 3c ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , copper appears to be the physiological inducer of ComR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>ComR did not regulate its own expression , but was required for copper-induction of the neighboring , divergently transcribed comC gene , as shown by real-time quantitative PCR and with a promoter-lux fusion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>These ﬁndings suggested that comC expression is modulated by the global regulators RpoE and CRP , in addition to the copper-dependent regulation by ComR shown here .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , induction of comC by copper via ComR is much more pronounced than the effects described for RpoE and CRP and we assume that copper-induction of comC is the principal regulation of this gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of comC was also determined in the comR knockout strain and was found to be increased by 270-fold on average , supporting the repression of ComC by ComR in the wild-type ( Fig. 2b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>The error bars indicate the standard deviation of three independent experiments 2 3 4 5 1 B A 100 60 50 43 37 25 20 0 1 2 3 4 8 16 32 64 C - R - Me Cu + Ag + Au3 + Co2 + Cd2 + Ni2 + ComR interaction + + Fragment F1-R1 D F1-R2 F1-R3 F1-R4 F2-R1 F3-R1 F3-R2 F3-R3 F4-R1 comR + + + ¬ ¬ ¬ ¬ comC 0 250 bp 200 150 100 50 E C omR - + + - + + - + + - + + - + + - + + - + + - + + - + + Cu - - + - - + - - + - - + - - + - - + - - + - - + - - + F1-R1 F1-R2 F1-R3 F1-R4 F2-R1 F3-R1 F4-R1 F3-R2 F3-R3 Fig. 3 Interaction of ComR with the comC promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">ComR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>This yielded a TetR-like structure for ComR with a potential copper-binding site formed by Cys-117 , Met-119 , and Gln-179 ( supplementary Figure S1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">ComR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>SczA and ComR are evolutionarily distant and share only 17 % sequence identity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>ComR shares 80 -- 90 % sequence identity with over 100 TetR-like transcriptional regulators in the protein database .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>ComR is predicted to encode a 210 amino acid protein which belongs to the family of TetR transcriptional regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_RP" for="_4"><font size="5px">Processes regulated by ComR</font></label>
				<input id="_4" type="checkbox">
				<div class="RP"><br><ul><li>ComR and ComC are thus two novel proteins involved in copper tolerance by E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both , ComC , and ComR are novel proteins involved in the response of E. coli to copper .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>ComR is a novel TetR-type copper-inducible repressor which regulates expression of the adjacent , inversely transcribed ycfR gene , which was renamed comC ( copper-induced outer membrane component ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>The copper-inducible ComR ( YcfQ ) repressor regulates expression of ComC ( YcfR ) , which affects copper permeability of the outer membrane of Escherichia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22751503" target="_blank">22751503</a>]<br></li>
<li>Biometals ( 2012 ) 25:33 -- 43 DOI 10.1007 / s10534-011-9510-x The copper-inducible ComR ( YcfQ ) repressor regulates expression of ComC ( YcfR ) , which affects copper permeability of the outer membrane of Escherichia coli Mélanie Mermod • David Magnani • Marc Solioz • Jivko V. Stoyanov Received : 10 April 2011 / Accepted : 9 July 2011 / Published online : 17 November 2011 Springer Science + Business Media , LLC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by ComR</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>ComR did not regulate its own expression , but was required for copper-induction of the neighboring , divergently transcribed comC gene , as shown by real-time quantitative PCR and with a promoter-lux fusion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of comC was also determined in the comR knockout strain and was found to be increased by 270-fold on average , supporting the repression of ComC by ComR in the wild-type ( Fig. 2b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cloning of ComR A ComR expression vector was constructed by PCR ampliﬁcation of the comR open reading frame from genomic DNA , using the primers ycfQHisF and ycfQHisR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>The resultant expression vector pProExComR was veriﬁed by sequencing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
